content.thinking:
Found it. The definitive nav styles are in `page-template.php` (the inline `<style>` block), not in `design-system.css`. The inline styles override the CSS files because they're in a `<style>` tag in the `<head>` after the linked CSS files.

Current nav layout (line 41):
```css
.site-nav { 
  position: fixed; 
  top: 16px; 
  left: 50%; 
  transform: translateX(-50%); 
  z-index: 100; 
  width: calc(100% - 48px); 
  max-width: 1180px; 
  background: transparent; 
  display: flex; 
  align-items: center; 
  justify-content: space-between; 
  gap: 1.5rem; 
}
```

The nav is centered and fixed at the top with the brand locked to the left, links in the middle without any flex growth, and the right section on the end.

The issue is that `justify-content: space-between` doesn't actually center the links properly since the brand and right sections have different widths — the links shift toward the right because the right side is wider with the booking button and language switcher. I should switch to CSS Grid with three columns instead: the brand gets the left column, nav-links takes the center with auto sizing, and the right section gets pushed to the end. This keeps the links truly centered regardless of how the other elements change size.

I need to update the inline style on `.site-nav` in `page-template.php` at line 41 to implement this grid layout and add `justify-self: end` to `.nav-right`.

